<TEXT>
riot police firing water cannons and tear 
gas broke up street protests in this capital city on wednesday 
during a communistled general strike that paralyzed transportation 
small pockets of strikers blocked streets with flaming tires and 
rubble before being driven off 
the government said 13 protesters were arrested in quito news 
reports said six people were detained in guayquil the nations 
financial center and largest city with 2 million people 180 miles 
southwest of the capital 
interior minister heinz moeller called the strike a failure he 
said nearly all of the nations labor force of 3 million workers 
ignored the strike call 
moeller told a news conference a capital policeman was injured 
by a firebomb tossed by a protester there were no other reports of 
injury 
strike leader fausto dutan said 80 percent of ecuadors business 
activity was halted by the strike called to back demands for 
higher pay 
radio reports said the strike had little impact in provincial 
cities across this andean nation which is the size of colorado and 
has 10 million people 
strike protests waned as night fell the downtown of this 
highland capital of 14 million residents was filled with tear gas 
making breathing difficult for the few pedestrians left on the 
streets 
president leon febres cordero said the strike the seventh 
during his tenure was illegal and declared a nationwide state of 
emergency 
combat troops were sent to guard electric generating plants 
gasoline stations and other installations riot police patrolled 
streets and industrial sectors of ecuadors major cities 
the nationwide strike was organized by the communistled united 
front of laborers the nations most powerful labor federation to 
seek wage increases 
dutan said the 200000member confederation wants the minimum 
monthly wage raised from 31 to 76 
moeller admitted that bus and taxi service in quito and 
guayaquil was nearly halted as drivers stayed off the job either in 
strike sympathy or in fear of violence 
many of quitos factories did not open because workers could not 
reach their jobs news reports said 
banks stores and shops in downtown quito opened normally or 
slightly late but closed in early afternoon to avoid trouble the 
government suspended school classes nationwide 
febres cordero a conservative whose fouryear term ends aug 
10 has faced increasing labor unrest over the past two years amid 
mounting economic woes caused mainly by depressed world prices for 
oil ecuadors main export 
rodrigo borja a lawyer who heads the democratic left party won 
a presidential runoff election in may to replace febres cordero 
moeller said the state of emergency which permits the 
government to deploy the military ban public meetings and censor 
the media would stay in force only until the strike officially 
ended at midnight wednesday 
</TEXT>
