<TEXT>
some republicans refer to firstterm sen 
jeff bingaman as the invisible senator and their conviction 
that he can be beaten has lured four candidates to seek the gop 
nomination in the june 7 primary 
bingaman is vulnerable because of his liberal voting record and 
his position on national defense issues said state gop chairman 
john lattauzio 
new mexicos congressmen philosophically have always supported 
defense spending until jeff bingaman came along he said and 
economically defense spending is very important to new mexico 
if we can articulate these issues effectively the republican 
candidate will do very well lattauzio said 
another thing we will be able to talk about a lot is that 
bingaman is the invisible senator new mexicans are accustomed to 
their congressmen staying in touch with them lattauzio said 
jeff just hasnt been around up until recently 
bingaman said in january when he announced for reelection that 
as one of only two firstterm democrats running this year the 
other is new jersey sen frank lautenberg he expected his race to 
be targeted by the national republican party 
but democrats question whether the republican field of state 
sens bill valentine 44 and joe carraro 43 both of albuquerque 
longtime party activist corky morris 52 of albuquerque and 
former us interior department official rick montoya 41 of las 
cruces can produce a strong challenger to bingaman 
polls showing a high percentage of undecided republicans far 
greater than the percentage favoring any candidate indicate none 
of the four has caught fire with the voters valentine and morris 
however appear to be the frontrunners 
lawrence ingram a former state democratic chairman said 
bingaman may be vulnerable but not with any of this years 
republican candidates 
those guys are all wallflowers who follow the old party 
line ingram said i think had the republicans had a 
charismatic candidate running against bingaman he would have a 
tough time in the fall 
valentine who sold his dentistry practice to campaign fulltime 
and carraro who owns and operates two pizza restaurants are 
giving up their state senate seats to try for the us senate 
morris who owns trucking and warehousing companies in 
albuquerque is a former state gop chairman and was new mexico 
chairman of the reaganbush campaign in 1984 
montoya left the reagan administration as assistant secretary of 
interior for terriorities and international affairs to return to 
new mexico and seek elective office for the first time 
bingaman who is unopposed in the democratic primary is a 
harvardeducated lawyer who in 1982 defeated firstterm republican 
sen harrison jack schmitt a former astronaut 
ingram said bingaman has recognized his problems and corrected 
most of them including that he had not been communicating with his 
constituency on a regular basis he also has been spending more 
time in new mexico in the last year meeting with residents 
the senate race and presidential voting top new mexicos primary 
ballot but the retirement after 20 years of republican rep manuel 
lujan jr has thrown open the door in the 1st congressional 
district 
three republicans including lujans younger brother edward and 
nine democrats aspire to succeed lujan who has called it quits 
after 20 years in congress 
edward lujan 55 is an albuquerque insurance executive and 
former state gop chairman challenging him are bernalillo county 
district attorney steven schiff 40 of albuquerque and state sen 
john budagher 41 of albuquerque 
the top democratic contenders are former state land commissioner 
jim baca 42 former state district judge patricia madrid 41 
bernalillo county commissioner lenton malry 57 city councilor 
steve gallegos 35 and former assistant us attorney tom udall 
39 all are from albuquerque 
