<TEXT>
the national economic commission created to 
solve the governments budget troubles is finding it tough to agree 
on just what that task entails 
commission cochairman robert strauss washington lawyer and 
political dealmaker says the mandate is clear the president 
and next congress need a political solution for reducing the 
federal deficit in the form of recommendations to close the gap 
between spending and taxes 
but commission member caspar weinberger the former defense 
secretary expressed surprise at a meeting tuesday when a witness 
suggested that making policy choices would be difficult 
are you suggesting that this commission is supposed to make 
specific recommendations for budget cuts and tax increases 
weinberger asked alice rivlin of the brookings institution a 
washington think tank 
weinberger and fellow republican donald rumsfeld another former 
defense secretary had focused their remarks on changing the 
cumbersome budget process the two former administration officials 
suggested changing the system to give the president more power over 
what they described as a spendthrift congress 
but rep william h gray iii dpa another commission member 
noted that president reagan has never submitted balanced budgets 
trying to blame congress for the deficits misses the point said 
gray the chairman of the house budget committee 
i thought we had to come up with specific recommendations 
said chrysler chairman lee iacocca another commission member 
by the end of the session strauss admonished the members not to 
get too tied up in possible philosophical differences strauss 
is cochairman of the 12member commission along with drew lewis 
president of the union pacific railroad and president reagans 
former transportation secretary 
ms rivlin a former director of the congressional budget 
office said the commission should seek ways to improve the process 
to keep the deficit under control in the long run but she said 
the panel will be a failure unless it proposes shortterm 
improvements as well 
congress created the commission last year to develop proposals 
for reducing the federal deficit its members were appointed by 
reagan and the bipartisan congressional leadership and two 
additional slots will be filled by the next president 
