<TEXT>
fourteen school and church groups are giving 
their imprimatur to a new pamphlet that lays out constitutional 
ways for public schools to teach about religion in a way that does 
not advocate a particular belief 
the sponsors said tuesday that endorsement of the document by 
such diverse groups as the national school boards association the 
national association of evangelicals and the research arm of 
americans united for separation of church and state indicates that 
the time is ripe for a resurgence of instruction about religion 
the question is no longer should we teach about religion 
charles c haynes of americans united told a news conference the 
question is how do we do this 
other participants called the 1000word pamphlet historic and 
expressed hope it will embolden teachers and principals to give 
religion its due in history literature and other classes 
james dunn of the baptist joint committee on public affairs said 
it shows there is a nobler and better way to deal with religion 
in public schools than simply to yell at each other and threaten a 
lawsuit 
all too often debates about religion in public schools have 
degenerated into a hogcalling or a shouting match dunn said 
secular and religious groups alike as well as secretary of 
education william j bennett have complained in recent years that 
religion gets short shrift in most american classrooms and 
textbooks even in courses that teach about historical events in 
which religion played a prominent part 
some critics blamed publishers fear of controversy while 
others attribute it to an overreaction by educators to supreme 
court rulings in the 1960s that barred statesponsored school 
prayer and bible reading 
the pamphlet provides guidance in questionandanswer form for 
school boards teachers and others 
the pamphlet called religion in the public school curriculum 
questions and answers notes that the supreme court has ruled 
unconstitutional a louisiana law that required schools to teach the 
biblical account of creation in science classes but it said the 
high court also acknowledged a variety of scientific theories about 
origins can appropriately be taught in a science class 
the pamphlet added though science instruction may not endorse 
or promote religious doctrine the account of creation found in 
various scriptures may be discussed in a religious studies class or 
in any course that considers religious explanations for the origin 
of life 
the pamphlet gives the following general advice on how to teach 
about religion 
the schools approach is academic not devotional 
the school may sponsor study about religion but may not 
sponsor the practice of religion 
the school may educate about all religions but may not 
promote or denigrate any religion 
the school may inform the student about various beliefs but 
should not seek to conform him or her to any particular belief 
because religion plays a significant role in history and 
society the pamphlet said study about religion is essential 
to understanding both the nation and the world omission of facts 
about religion can give students the false impression that the 
religious life of humankind is insignificant or unimportant 
failure to understand even the basic symbols practices and 
concepts of the various religions makes much of history 
literature art and contemporary life unintelligible 
the pamphlet recommends careful handling of religious 
holidays in the classroom with information focusing on the 
origin history and generally agreedupon meaning of the 
observances 
other sponsors include the american academy of religion 
national school boards association the american association of 
school administrators the christian legal society the national 
conference of christians and jews the national council of churches 
of christ the national council for the social studies the 
association for supervision and curriculum development the 
american federation of teachers and the national education 
association 
</TEXT>
