<TEXT>
up to 240 pregnant women were given a drug linked 
to birth defects without their knowledge as part of a study and 
officals are considering disciplining the researchers 
dilantin a drug commonly used to treat epilepsy was given by 
two cook county hospital anesthesiologists to about 245 pregnant 
women to determine whether it could reduce fetal stress in 
caesarean births hospital spokesman terrence hansen said tuesday 
five of the women had consented to participate in the 
hospitalapproved study from september 1987 through january said 
dr robert miller chairman of the hospitals scientific committee 
the other women were given the drug without their knowledge and 
without approval from the hospitals review board said miller 
who unlike hansen said he understood that only some of these 
approximately 240 women were pregnant 
miller said dilantin has been linked to birth defects when 
administered early in pregnancy but he said the women received the 
drug 15 minutes before delivering their babies 
the president of the cook county board which oversees the 
hospital said he would hold a meeting monday to discuss punishment 
for the doctors who have not been identified 
i was appalled to think that men in the medical profession 
would do that board president george dunne said tuesday they 
of all people should know that you dont experiment on patients 
without obtaining their written consent 
the illinois department of public health which regulates the 
licensing of hospitals is aware of the doctors action but is 
barred by state law from revealing whether it is investigating 
said spokeswoman penny strong 
spokesman terry levin of the cook county states attorneys 
office declined to comment on whether his office was investigating 
to see if criminal laws were violated 
the women all received a single smallerthannormal dose of the 
drug hansen said two of the babies died because of unrelated 
complications hansen said 
several studies have reported higher incidences of birth 
defects including heart abnormalities and retardation among 
babies born to women who use dilantin and other antiepileptic 
drugs 
miller said he did not agree with the doctors actions but did 
not consider them unethical 
but a medical ethicist called the practice a serious abuse 
of the medical profession 
it seems to me that it simply goes against the principles of 
biomedical ethics which really require that any person 
enrolled in a research project be informed of that and be given a 
chance to consent or refuse said james childress a religion and 
medical education professor at the university of virginia 
what it amounts to is basically using human beings as 
means to other ends not treating them as ends in themselves 
he said even though the risk was limited it was still a serious 
abuse 
hansen said the failure to gain the womens consent was a 
violation of hospital policy 
the hospitals executive medical staff recommended may 18 that 
the doctors be given probation a warning that would pave the way 
for stricter measures if they further violate hospital policy 
hansen said 
an ultimate decision on what action is taken against the 
doctors would rest with the board of trustees which is to meet 
monday hansen said 
hansen said none of the women has sued the hospital 
