federal government if its taxes thats where it has to be 
bushs comments came as he repeated his oftstated opposition to 
a federal tax increase 
ive pledged no tax increase and im going to stay with it 
period bush said 
the vice president speaking after meeting with a group of 
private economists also cautioned the federal reserve board 
against clamping down too tightly on credit in the name of fighting 
inflation 
im not hypercritical of the fed but i dont want to see 
action taken thats going to shut down economic growth in this 
country bush said 
the deficitreduction panel formed earlier this year plans to 
submit its recommendations to congress on dec 21 in addition to 
members appointed by the reagan administration and by both parties 
in congress the panel will have two members named by whoever wins 
the election in november 
it seems to me that the commission might well come up with a 
tax increase and ill be saying wait a minute ive taken my 
case to the american people to hold the line on taxes 
bush has proposed eliminating the budget deficit with what he 
calls a flexible freeze on spending all programs except 
social security benefits would be held at 1989 levels plus 
inflation increases in one area would have to be offset by 
decreases in another 
the vice president holds a second day of talks today with the 
same group of economic advisers among them is martin s feldstein 
a harvard economist who quit his job as president reagans chief 
economist in 1985 when his advocacy of a tax increase to reduce the 
budget deficit ran afoul of the administrations stance against 
general tax increases 
bush said that during his meeting tuesday with the economic 
advisers there was an expression of hoping that fed policy would 
not be too tight 
i think watching for signs of inflation is fine bush said 
but as a word of caution i wouldnt want to see them step over 
some boundary that would ratchet down tighten down the economic 
growth 
the nation is in its 65th month of economic expansion a 
peacetime record an economic downturn before the election could 
spell big troubles for republicans election prospects most 
economic and political consultants agree 
the bush campaign has been having some economic problems of its 
own lately a shortage of cash 
two months ago bush aides reported that they only had 4 
million left to spend before the republican convention aide robert 
teeter said tuesday that the amount has now dwindled to just under 
15 million 
the vice president said over the weekend that the squeeze may 
mean some curtailing of campaign travel in the weeks ahead 
the bush campaign has had no trouble raising money but it is 
close to bumping up against the preconvention federal spending 
limit of 27 million 
the campaign has raised 295 million of which about 25 is 
not subject to the ceiling 
