8000 in compensation from the government for her mental anguish 
i have long suspected that the supreme court was an 
institution obsequious to the powerful today im sorry to see 
that the court is mrs nakaya told reporters after the decision 
takako doi leader of the major opposition japan socialist 
party told the same news conference i would call the ruling a 
compromise by the guardian of the constitution made in favor of the 
governments way of thinking 
i feel like were being driven back to the past mrs doi 
said 
mrs nakaya has said she filed the suit to challenge the 
possible revival of the militarism that revolved around japans 
traditional shintoism before and during world war ii 
before 1945 soldiers killed in action or while on duty were 
automatically given the status of gods and their names were 
inscribed in shinto shrines 
the practice was discontinued under the new constitution which 
guarantees freedom of religion and was written under us guidance 
after japans defeat but soldiers killed on duty are sometimes 
enshrined at the request of the association of retired self defense 
forces members called taiyukai 
in its 141 vote wednesday the supreme court said the armed 
forces were not directly involved in the case of lt nakaya and 
that the taiyukai had him enshrined the lower courts had ruled 
that the armed forces had a direct role in the enshrinement 
shintoism is said to have emerged at the dawn of japanese 
history and crystalized as a religious system during the nara 
period in the eighth century 
as the state religion before 1945 it stressed the divinity of 
the emperor and the worship of nature ancestors and ancient 
heroes the military used shinto shrines and ceremonies to promote 
nationalism among the japanese 
the rev mototsugu ogata chief guardian of the gokoku shrine in 
yamaguchi said in a telephone interview lt nakaya is one of a 
total of 52099 enshrined in a big tall sacred mirror at this 
shrine established in 1941 they are mostly those killed in 
world war ii 
like the others nakayas name has been written in a sacred list 
as mikoto takafumi nakaya said the shinto priest mikoto 
is the shinto term for god or deity 
the religion respects several types of deities including 
ancestral gods gods revered for virtues gods revered for their 
works and gods whose wrath is to be feared 
shintoism a religion of ceremony rather than dogma coexists in 
japan with buddhism the other major religion the exact number of 
adherents is not known and many japanese practice both religions 
there are also about 1 million christians among the 122 million 
japanese 
</TEXT>
