<TEXT>
sinhalese extremists on wednesday 
burned more than 15 government buildings stabbed a policeman to 
death and injured eight people with a bomb in attacks aimed at 
stopping provincial elections 
the government responded by ordering police and security forces 
to shoot on sight anyone caught destroying government property 
the elections are scheduled for thursday to comply with a 
provision of a peace accord aimed at ending the minority tamils 
fiveyear insurgency 
extremists among the majority sinhalese say the pact made too 
many concessions to the tamils and have vowed to kill anyone who 
supports it 
government officials speaking on condition of anonymity said 
explosions and fire also damaged three trains bound for colombo on 
wednesday 
one of the trains was stopped by three gunwielding youths in 
nebomob 20 miles north of colombo said the officials and 
travelers the youths believed to be sinhalese extremists ordered 
passengers off the train and then set two of the coaches ablaze 
with gasoline no injuries were reported 
the policeman was stabbed by three sinhalese in the southern 
town of galle said a police spokesman who spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
he said one sinhalese extremist was shot to death in an 
encounter with police north of colombo and a second died when a 
firebomb he was going to throw at a government building just south 
of colombo blew up in his hand 
in another attack four government officials and four policemen 
were seriously injured when a bomb went off in nuwara eilyas town 
hall 60 miles east of colombo as poll workers prepared for 
thursdays voting police blamed the attack on the nationalist 
sinhalese peoples liberation front 
the front told people in the election area to stay inside for 36 
hours and put up posters threatening to kill anyone who tried to 
vote 
the police spokesman said more than 15 government buildings were 
set ablaze by the sinhalese extremists mostly in western and 
southern districts the buildings included post offices 
development offices and town halls he said 
businessmen said extremists ordered them to shutter their shops 
and many merchants said they complied for fear of reprisal some of 
the shops opened later in the day 
government announcements on staterun radio and television said 
police have been given orders to shoot on sight any person 
engaged in the destruction of public property and said the 
elections would go ahead 
the voting thursday is to elect new district councils in the 
western and central provinces the capital at colombo in the 
western province 
more than 36 million voters are eligible to vote in the 
elections to choose 158 representatives 
the balloting was called for in the peace accord signed on july 
29 1987 by prime minister rajiv gandhi of india and sri lankan 
president junius r jayewardene the signing led to rioting in 
which several hundred people were killed or injured 
the government blamed the sinhalese front for instigating the 
riots the violence on wednesday was the worst since those riots 
the front has been blamed for the deaths of more than 300 people 
since the pact was signed many of them government officials or 
members of jayewardenes governing united national party several 
candidates were killed before district council elections april 28 
in four other regions 
tamil rebels have been waging a guerrilla war since 1983 for 
more political autonomy or an independent homeland in northern and 
eastern sri lanka 
tamils who are mostly hindus and make up 18 percent of sri 
lankas 16 million population say they are discriminated against 
by the sinhalese who control the government and military 
india has become involved because it is the dominant regional 
power and because its 60 million ethnic tamils are sympathetic to 
the sri lankan cause 
india has sent more than 50000 troops to the island to enforce 
the accord but they are posted in the north and east to deal with 
tamil problems 
the sinhalese front was outlawed after an abortive attempt in 
1971 to overthrow the sri lankan government it has been regrouping 
in recent years and has been blamed for a series of violent acts 
including the attempted assassination of jayewardene in august 1987 
