traffic scofflaws are getting relief not from 
the fines but from lines at court 
three first independent money stores soon will accept fine 
payments in a program that will help clear 36th district court 
which processed more than 400000 traffic violations last year 
chief judge adam a shakoor said 
the money stores owned by first independence national bank 
detroits only minorityowned bank will get a 50cent fee from 
each ticket 
traffic violations can be paid by mail but people too poor to 
maintain bank accounts are unable do so because fines must be paid 
with a check or money order thirty percent are paid in person 
shakoor said 
the 36th district court is a peoples court and we intend to 
provide more communityoriented services that will ultimately make 
the court run more smoothly shakoor said 
beginning june 13 motorists can pay fines on all traffic 
violations the program may be expanded for parking violations 
first independence which opened the money stores more than a 
year ago to provide banking services to lowerincome detroit 
residents lost 500000 on the stores last year and expects to 
lose 230000 this year 
the fees collected from the fine payments will help said don 
davis chairman of first independence 
the money stores were chosen for the program because the 
facilities have computer systems that are compatible with the 
courts shakoor said adding officials eventually hope to make the 
service available at other banking institutions shakoor said he 
knew of no other program like detroits in the country 
