<TEXT>
theyre alive and well but children who undergo 
kidney transplants are also extremely short because the medication 
they take to ensure the transplant isnt rejected hinders their 
growth doctors say 
since young kidney recipients want to grow normally doctors are 
trying new therapies with some success to help them in body and 
spirit 
theyre taller and theyre much happier said dr amir 
tejani director of renal services at the state university of new 
york health science center at brooklyn 
about onefourth of all young kidney recipients can be treated 
successfully without a steroid commonly combined with the potent 
antirejection drug cyclosporine tejani reported tuesday at the 
annual conference of the american society of transplant physicians 
the steroid known as prednisone inhibits the growth plate in 
the bone from functioning normally it also causes acne and 
puffiness most noticeably in the face 
this is a very important study since the whole point of doing 
transplants is to achieve growth said dr william harmon a 
nephrologist at childrens hospital in boston 
even for a third of them to grow normally then by all means 
we should be doing this for our kids or at least trying said dr 
lawrence g hunsicker the societys president 
like children suffering from other serious illnesses children 
with kidney failure tend to be extraordinarily short sometimes 
barely topping 4 feet 
by the time they undergo a transplant its often too late for 
these children to catch up on past growth even if they receive 
transplants at a very young age the medication necessary for 
helping to prevent their bodies immune systems from attacking the 
new organ stunts their growth 
perhaps the bestknown case involves gary coleman star of the 
former television series diffrent strokes the 19yearold 
actor whos undergone two kidney transplants is under 5 feet tall 
the issue is a big one for these children said dr ira 
greifer medical director of the national kidney foundation a 
lot of the patients especially the younger ones want to take the 
risk of rejection for the extra inches 
some patients in fact cheat on their medication in a desperate 
attempt to improve their appearance according to tejani 
you cant tell them it doesnt matter if theyre short when 
it matters to them greifer said you cant tell them the world 
is made up of small people when americans are getting taller 
about 1200 youngsters 16 and under experience kidney failure 
every year in the united states according to greifer six hundred 
to 800 of them eventually receive new kidneys they comprise fewer 
than 9 percent of the total number of kidney transplants performed 
annually 
the operation is quite successful one year after 
transplantation up to 85 percent of them still have properly 
functioning kidneys according to experts 
for his research tejani studied 53 children and selected 30 
whose transplanted kidneys were functioning well enough to undergo 
the experiment the 30 were taken off prednisone 
twentythree of them proved to be treatable solely with 
cyclosporine at the time however nine of the 23 had to return to 
prednisone later after experiencing mild episodes of organ 
rejection tejani said 
the remaining 14 a little more than onefourth of the original 
53 children in the study have been off prednisone for up to 4 
years without any episodes of organ rejection or side effects 
according to tejani more important all of them have grown 
including one 17yearold boy who has reached 5 feet 8 inches 
in patients unable to be weaned off prednisone tejani has 
administered growth hormone enabling them to catch up on some of 
their lost growth 
doctors at the university of california at los angeles also have 
begun giving growth hormone to certain kidney transplant patients 
as well as children on dialysis 
the data seems good said dr vera h koch a clinical 
fellow at ucla there seems to be hope 
</TEXT>
