<TEXT>
orders to us factories surged for the second 
consecutive month in april the government said wednesday 
indicating that us manufacturing plants will be humming in the 
months ahead 
the commerce department said orders for durable and nondurable 
goods rose a strong 12 percent to a seasonally adjusted 2187 
billion in april the advance followed an even bigger 16 percent 
increase in march 
the boomlike conditions in factory america continue pretty 
much unabated said allen sinai chief economist of the boston co 
there was no change in order levels in february and a modest 06 
percent drop in january but that was one of only two declines in 
the past year 
most economists had been forecasting only modest growth in new 
orders of 05 percent in april the biggerthanexpected number 
likely will do little to alleviate concern among some analysts that 
strong demand particularly for exports will trigger greater 
inflation 
david wyss chief financial economist at data resources inc a 
lexington mass forecasting firm noted the continuing increase 
in the backlog of unfilled orders indicating manufacturers have 
been getting more orders than they can meet 
this should be good news for production in coming months 
wyss said 
the backlog of 4181 billion was 108 percent higher than a 
year ago it jumped by 1 percent in april following a smaller 
increase of 04 percent in march 
the strength in new orders in april came in electrical 
machinery lumber and wood products and in petroleum chemicals and 
paper 
the department revised its estimate of new orders for durable 
goods big ticket items expected to last three or more years 
to 1164 billion up 10 percent the previous estimate for april 
released 10 days ago was 08 percent the gain in march had been 
08 percent 
orders for nondurable goods increased 15 percent to 1022 
billion in april following a 25 percent rise a month earlier 
excluding the volatile category of military goods orders were 
up 12 percent in april the third consecutive increase and the 
sixth rise in seven months 
defense goods rose 22 percent to 100 billion in april 
following a whopping 146 percent rise in march 
the key category of nondefense capital goods considered a 
barometer of business expansion plans rose 19 percent in april to 
331 billion following a drop of 38 percent 
analysts are looking for businesses to boost capital spending to 
meet the rising demand abroad for us goods which have become 
more competitively priced because of the devalued dollar 
orders for electrical machinery climbed 42 percent following a 
38 percent slide in march most of the april strength in that 
category came from a large 254 percent rise in orders for 
communication equipment most of them from the defense department 
orders for primary metals such as steel declined 03 percent in 
april while orders for transportation equipment climbed a slight 
01 percent and nonelectrical machinery fell 06 percent 
shipments of manufactured goods were unchanged at 2146 billion 
in april following a 27 percent increase in march 
