the federal aviation administration plans to 
play a greater role in keeping aviation out of the drug trafficking 
business the agencys chief said wednesday 
faa administrator allan mcartor announced he is assigning 13 
people within the faa to a special office that will deal 
exclusively with illegal drug trafficking issues 
this is a serious problem and we want to be a serious 
player mcartor told reporters after disclosing his antidrug 
plans in a speech to the international aviation club 
mcartor said he wasnt ready to provide details as to exactly 
what the new faa office would do except to say it would coordinate 
the agencys efforts to battle the smuggling of illegal drugs by 
air 
were going to be developing their mission as we go along 
mcartor said adding that the group may be expanded in the future 
he said the faa officials would have no enforcement or police 
powers and that he had no intention of confiscating commercial 
aircraft should small amounts of drugs be found 
the coast guard and customs service recently have been 
criticized for confiscating expensive yachts under a zero 
tolerance antidrug enforcement program when only small amounts 
of an illegal drug were found 
mcartor said the new faa office would consist of agency security 
officers inspectors and perhaps even air traffic controllers 
the shift of manpower from the inspector and controller ranks 
comes at a time when the faa has acknowledged shortages in both 
areas mcartor conceded that the commitment of 13 people is a big 
deal for the agency but that he wants the faa to become a full 
player in the war against illegal drugs 
he also suggested the airlines and private pilot groups begin 
to help police themselves to keep illegal drugs out of our 
industry 
