<TEXT>
an aviation industry stunned by the inflight 
breakup last month of an aloha airlines jet began a formal 
reexamination wednesday of how to ensure that aging aircraft are 
kept safe 
more than 350 representatives from airlines aircraft 
manufacturers government agencies and various aviation safety 
groups launched a threeday conference by debating whether the 
industrys approach to maintaining the safety of older planes is 
adequate 
faa administrator allan mcartor suggested that a central 
question which must be resolved is whether to continue the current 
philosophy that relies heavily on inspections or shift the focus to 
a system of mandatory repairs or at some point mandatory aircraft 
retirement 
concerns about aging aircraft among the commercial airliner 
fleets surfaced last month when a 20foot section of an aloha 
airlines boeing 737 tore away at 24000 feet a flight attendant 
was swept to her death but the pilots managed to get the plane on 
the ground 
the 19yearold aloha plane was one of the oldest boeing 737s in 
service and had accumulated nearly 90000 takeoffs and landings 
investigators believe cracking and corrosion in the upper forwared 
part of the cabin likely caused the section of the plane to peel 
away during flight 
the central question confronting wednesdays conference centered 
on why the apparent cracking and corrosion on the aloha plane were 
not detected by inspectors an faa directive last year had required 
closer inspection of older aircraft for cabin skin cracking and 
corrosion 
during the threeday meeting the industry representatives are 
expected to debate whether aircraft design improvements need to be 
made and what steps need to be taken to improve the maintenance and 
inspection process so that such failures will not occur in the 
future 
i think we might find that the procedures are adequate but 
im not convinced the procedures are being done with as much 
discipline as we might expect mcartor suggested in remarks to 
reporters he said he did not expect any conclusive findings to 
come out of the conference but said it likely will spawn 
additional private sessions in the coming months on the aging 
aircraft issue 
several members of congress addressed the group and raised 
concerns about the maintenenance of older jetliners 
rep dan glickman dkan suggested that the faa buy old 
jetliners and test them to determine when a plane no longer can be 
considred safe 
only by answering the question how long can airplanes really 
last will we be able to put into place guideines which could save 
thousands of lives said glickman 
but william hoover of the air transport associaton the airline 
trade group said that aircraft if properly maintained and 
inspected can be flown safely throughout their economically 
useful life and well beyond their design life 
one of the questions confronting the conference however is 
whether the industry should continue to use economic life as 
the key factor in determining when a plane should be taken of 
service suggested john enders an aviation consultant for the 
flight safety foundation 
as for the heavy emphasis on inspections glickman said the 
aloha accident demonstrates the inadequacies of the faas 
maintenance inspection system aloha airlines officials have said 
repeatedly that they followed all required inspections on the 
boeing 737 that broke apart in flight 
it obviously wasnt sufficient said enders the aviation 
consultant the aloha inspections were not enough to give the 
early warning signs 
