those talks grew out of the 1975 helsinki accords in which the 
soviets pledged to observe human rights for 13 years the united 
states has accused the kremlin of violating the accords and soviet 
officials are now conceding as much releasing political prisoners 
and allowing greater public discussion of formerly taboo subjects 
many americans including sen sam nunn dga chairman of the 
senate armed services committee believe that sharp reductions in 
conventional forces should accompany the 30 percent to 50 percent 
cuts in longrange nuclear missiles envisioned in the proposed 
strategic arms reduction treaty 
from the american point of view the main objectives of reducing 
conventional arms would be a reduction in the 2to1 advantage the 
warsaw pact holds on tanks and a reduction in the 380000 red army 
troops in east germany 
although the edge may have dulled on reagans anticommunist 
rhetoric his schedule was designed to emphasize us concern with 
human rights he met with nearly 100 soviet dissidents at the 
residence of the american ambassador he pointedly praised the 
virtues of american democracy at every turn he chatted with with 
writers artists and students 
and us officials let it be known that reagan had canceled a 
meeting with the zieman family of jewish refuseniks because a 
highranking soviet official had warned that a visit to their home 
would kill their application to emigrate 
much of the hardball was being played behind the scenes said a 
senior administration official noting that the american and the 
soviet regularly but quietly were engaged in discussion of human 
rights issues 
the presidents statements would be hard to explain unless 
there was something going on behind the scenes and his spoken 
words were particularly puzzling in light of his extracurricular 
activities at the summit which appeared designed to focus 
attention on soviet human rights policy especially the 
difficulties that jews face in emigrating 
but on tuesday reagan told students at moscow state university 
that recalcitrant bureaucrats were to blame for soviet human rights 
abuses and under pointed questioning at a news conference on 
wednesday reagan said similar problems could be found everywhere 
i just have to believe that in any sort of government some of 
us do find ourselves bound in by bureaucracy reagan said 
and after four days of talks with gorbachev he expressed 
confidence that the kremlin leader was trying and would succeed in 
improving the situation 
soviet human rights activists attributed reagans comments on 
human rights to naivete 
the bureaucracy has nothing to do with it said tanya 
zieman whose family had waited in vain for reagans visit on 
sunday 
reagan and his aides may have been calculating that having made 
their views known in moscow they should tone down the rhetoric in 
hopes of winning longsought cuts in soviet conventional forces in 
eastern europe 
