bipartisan package of deficitreduction proposals 
the panel which will also include two members appointed by the 
new presidentelect in november will submit its report in 1989 
democratic critics as well as many private economists argue 
that it is unlikely the budget deficit 150 billion last year can 
be eliminated without some form of new taxes 
bushs proposal calls for a flexible freeze that would keep 
overall spending except for social security payments at levels in 
the budget approved by congress for fiscal year 1989 plus 
inflation 
the freeze would be flexible because some spending could go up 
but increases would have to be offset by identical reductions in 
other areas 
