the state department of public health sampled water at 79 public 
and two private elementary schools over the memorial day weekend 
after a television station reported high lead content at eight 
schools 
water at 40 schools exceeded the epa limit of 50 parts per 
million of lead in drinking water the tests revealed a level of 
2300 parts per million at the water supply source in one school 
and 1400 ppm at a water fountain in another 
keough said the epa in july plans to recommend reducing the 
unsafe lead content level to 20 ppm the tests showed an additional 
19 schools had lead concentrations of between 20 and 50 ppm 
lead poisoning attacks the brain kidneys nervous system and 
red blood cells and can lead to brain damage and death health 
officials said lead occurs in food air soil dust paint and 
water 
officials said poisoning is rarely caused by contaminated water 
alone but overexposure to lead can stunt physical and mental 
development in children causing nervous disorders learning 
disabilities and mental problems children under 8 are especially 
vulnerable they added 
ralph timperi director of the state laboratory institute in 
boston which analyzed the water samples said three likely sources 
for the lead are lead pipes lead solder used from 198086 and 
electric cooling systems in water fountains some lead pipes in 
boston schools are more than 50 years old he said 
schools are more susceptible to high lead levels because water 
sits in pipes after school and on weekends allowing greater lead 
absorption 
in a 1976 study the epa found that 25 percent of bostonarea 
households exceeded federal lead safety limits 
keough said officials will attack the problem on a fountain by 
fountain basis by repairing or replacing pipes solder and 
cooling systems 
