<TEXT>
rising interest rates have come knocking on the 
housing and construction industries threatening to blow down five 
straight years of solid gains in nationwide sales 
but economists say the cyclical big bad wolf isnt likely to 
cause too much damage in 1988 although the outlook for the next 
couple of years remains in question 
it will be a weaker year than it could have been because of 
interest rates but were still expecting a good year said 
john tuccillo chief economist for the national association of 
realtors 
tuccillo estimated that sales of existing homes would total 33 
million and new home sales would total 650000 in 1988 down from 
365 million and 690000 respectively last year 1987 but still 
among the strongest years this decade 
a report released tuesday by the commerce and housing and urban 
development departments said that newhome sales climbed 4 percent 
in april to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 679000 the 
third consecutive rise and the fastest pace since new homes sold at 
a rate of 728000 in april 1987 
in a report last week the national association of realtors said 
sales of existing homes rose 45 percent last month after increases 
of 25 percent in both march and february 
while economists said the reports show solid gains they 
cautioned that consumers rushed to do their buying then before 
interest rates headed higher they said may might not be as strong 
people are trying to negotiate a settlement and get a mortgage 
in the face of a fairly certain rise in interest rates said 
george a christie chief economist with the fw dodge division of 
mcgrawhill information systems co 
mortgage rates are actually slightly lower now than they were a 
year ago averaging about 1046 percent for a 30year fixedrate 
conventional mortgage vs an average 1060 percent in may 1987 
according to the federal home loan mortgage corp known as freddie 
mac 
but after falling sharply since the oct 19 stock market crash 
rates started to creep up again over the past several weeks on 
fears that the economy may be overheating and inflation might be on 
the rise the 30year mortgage rate for instance has risen more 
than half a percentage point since february when it averaged 989 
percent freddie mac said 
many economists predict mortgage rates will continue to rise 
through the summer and top 11 percent by the end of the year a 
handful are forecasting rates in excess of 12 percent in 1989 at 
the same time experts are calling for moderate inflation of around 
5 percent this year 
frank nothaft deputy chief economist for freddie mac said the 
rise in fixedrate mortgages may cause some wouldbe homebuyers to 
switch to adjustable rate mortgages he said some savings and loan 
associations also will become more accommodative for instance by 
requiring smaller down payments or lowering closing costs to 
encourage sales 
