<TEXT>
if youve been hearing for weeks about the 
postcrash stock markets malaise youre probably wondering what 
has sent prices surging higher so suddenly welcome to the crowd 
seasoned market watchers expressed surprise at the buying spree 
following the long memorial day weekend that sent the languishing 
dow jones industrial average up more than 100 points in two days 
it soared nearly 75 points tuesday the biggest oneday rise 
since the beginning of the year and tacked on 33 more on wednesday 
many analysts said the rally once again proved the adage that 
you cannot outguess the market but some veteran economists warned 
that they saw no development that should so radically improve wall 
streets gloomy outlook for inflation and higher interest rates 
evidence of rising inflation persists from the chicago 
commodity pits to the neighborhood grocery checkout strains on 
americas productive abilities coupled with fears of a profound 
farm drought this summer are intensifying upward pressure on 
prices 
theres only one way to start writing this story once upon a 
time robert brusca chief economist of nikko securities co 
international in new york said in response to the stock markets 
abrupt surge its a bit of a fairy tale out there 
explanations for the turnaround included speculation that the 
federal reserve will not tighten credit further a realization that 
the economy is healthy and a postholiday tendency to buy stocks 
some economists said the markets reversal confirmed their view 
that inflation is not a big problem 
a few even suggested president reagans performance at the 
moscow summit injected a euphoric mood into the market that hasnt 
been seen since last summer well before the stunning collapse of 
oct 19 
but others said they simply did not know why the market had 
reversed course 
its a very good question said robert stovall a new 
yorkbased stock market forecaster the serenity could be 
shortlived everything thats happened has been given a positive 
bias or ignored 
some economists who scrutinize the links between markets were 
disturbed by wall streets big gain partly because it defied a 
logical pattern that had developed between stocks bonds and 
commodity prices 
in that relationship when commodity prices rise bonds fall 
over the consequent fear of inflation and depress stocks as well 
but on tuesday commodity prices jumped while stocks and bonds 
also rose 
on balance whats going on with the stock and bond markets 
does not ring true brusca said the trap door is going to open 
up again and suck everybody down 
michael moran chief economist at daiwa securities america in 
new york speculated the wall street rally reflected growing 
investor hopes of no further moves to tighten credit by the federal 
reserve he said rising commodity prices were based on fear of 
drought not a broad inflationary move 
in that environment inflation fears subside and the market 
can do a bit better moran said 
the fed already has moved a few times this year to nudge 
interest rates higher through its control of the amount of money in 
the banking system there had been speculation last week that the 
fed would take a more drastic step by announcing an increase in the 
discount rate the loan fee it charges financial institutions the 
rate has remained at 6 percent since sept 4 
some market watchers said it was pointless to speculate about 
the shortterm ups and downs of stock prices because meaningful 
trends can only be detected over a long period 
robert sobel a wall street historian and professor who has 
written several books on the market said he would advise investors 
to ignore most economists predictions of stock behavior because 
they are so unreliable 
theyd be better off using nancy reagans astrologist sobel 
said i think these people are vastly overpaid they dont know 
what theyre doing most of the time 
