by federal german police us authorities said wednesday 
hans joachim schmidt 38 a former currency trader from 
frankfurt has exhausted his extradition appeals said jim sanders 
of the us attorneys office 
in the warrant for schmidts arrest and the extradition request 
he is charged with forgery of documents and instigation of 
embezzlement in a scheme in which employees of volkswagenwerk ag 
were persuaded to enter into foreign currency transactions as part 
of a secret profitsharing agreement 
schmidt was arrested on a fugitive warrant in november 1987 at 
his hollywood apartment where he was living under an assumed name 
a special team of west german federal police was created a year 
ago to hunt for schmidt who fled in march 1987 after the discovery 
of alleged fraudulent foreign exchange deals that cost volkswagen 
about 2824 million 
volkswagen said it first discovered the fraud when the national 
bank of hungary refused to honor a contract calling on it to buy 
dollars from volkswagen 
while he was a fugitive schmidt traveled through switzerland 
several southern european countries and the caribbean west german 
police said 
prosecutors in the northern west german city of braunschweig 
have alleged that schmidt and several former volkswagen employees 
defrauded the giant automaker by falsifying financial instruments 
known as forward contracts 
such contracts are used by large international companies like 
volkswaggen to protect themselves from currency fluctuations 
schmidt is accused of putting profits from the currency exchange 
deals into secret bank accounts in switzerland and lichtenstein 
