<TEXT>
seven ethanol producers filed a 21 
billion antitrust lawsuit in district court on wednesday alleging 
that four major oil companies conspired to discourage the sale of 
ethanol 
the defendants are shell oil co marathon petroleum co amoco 
oil co and chevron usa inc 
bob wright of lafayette la one of the attorneys who filed the 
lawsuit charged that the oil companies made inaccurate and 
misleading statements against gasohol a blend of 10 percent 
ethanol and 90 percent gasoline 
the clearest evidence of what the oil companies have done is 
labeling wright said at a news conference 
he said signs at some of the oil companies service stations 
say our gasoline contains no alcohol or ethanol or our 
gasoline is clean 
those sorts of signs and labels would clearly infer there 
is something wrong with alcohol or ethanol wright said 
spokespeople for the oil companies had no immediate comment 
as a result of the oil companies campaign wright said the 
ethanol market has effectively dried up with producers 
suffering significant economic damages 
the plaintiffs include greater rockford energy and technology 
corp of rockford ill shepherd oil inc of jennings la 
vidalia ethanol ltd of vidalia la alpebo inc of jennings 
la shreveport ethanol inc of shreveport la lakefield ethanol 
inc of lakefield minn and a e montana inc of amsterdam mont 
ethanol is made from corn and if the ethanol industry had been 
allowed to grow wright said it would have had a tremendous 
effect on agriculture 
wright said ethanol also is good for the environment since it 
can reduce harmful emissions from automobile exhausts 
the lawsuit also said the defendants refused to accept 
creditcard invoices from gasohol sales and terminated some 
retailers or distributors who did accept creditcard invoices for 
gasohol purchases 
the companies also limited the availability of gasohol to 
consumers and refused to communicate or deal directly with the 
plaintiffs the lawsuit contended 
the ethanol manufacturers are asking for three times their 
actual damages of 700 million and for an injunction to stop the 
defendants from engaging in practices allegedly designed to hurt 
the ethanol market 
where this industry be without oil companies negatively 
advertising against our product would be speculation but i believe 
it would be a lot larger said steve wentworth first vice 
president of the national corn growers association the bottom 
line here is marketshare the major oil companies dont want to 
give it up to independent blenders 
</TEXT>
